**Using genotype data to identify duplicate accessions and find parents.**

Basic example:  
	In this example we start with a vcf file which has diploid genotypes for 8759 accessions at 5621 markers. The genotypes are phased and the vcf file includes estimated probabilities for each genotype. Here is an example analysis using default parameters:

Convert from vcf format to the ‘dsgm’ (dosage matrix) format used by the other programs:

	vcf_to_dsgm  -vcf cassava.vcf  -out cassava.dsgm  

Find pairs of similar accessions:

	duplicate_search  -in cassava.dsgm  -out cassava.dsout

The output has 6 columns:  &ensp; id\_1  &ensp;  missing\_data\_count\_1  &ensp; id\_2  &ensp;  missing\_data\_count\_2  &ensp;  agmr  &ensp;  hgmr

agmr is the fraction of markers with different genotypes in the two accessions. 

Find clusters of duplicate accessions:

	clusterer  -in cassava.dsout -out cassava.clustout

Running this way using default parameters may be reasonable, but different genotyping error rates will give different observed agmrs between duplicate accessions. So it is a good idea to make a histogram of the agmr values (column 5\) of the output from duplicate\_search to decide how similar accessions should be (i.e. how small the agmr should be) to be considered duplicates. The default value of this parameter is 0.035 ; a different value can be specified when running clusterer with e.g.:   \-dcluster  0.04  . Let’s look at the histogram to see if this is reasonable. 

![alt text](cassava\_dsout\_agmr\_histogram\_480x360.png "title")  

There is a clear peak at about 0.014, and it extends up to about 0.03 . This suggests these are due to duplicates whose observed genotypes differ due to a genotyping error rate of \~0.7%. The default value looks quite reasonable.

Remove duplicate accessions:  
I.e. from each cluster of duplicates keep only one (the one with the least missing data). 

	uniquify  -dosages_in  cassava.dsgm  -cluster cassava.clustout

If we have a record of the parents of accessions we can also supply the name of the file containing that pedigree information to uniquify:

	uniquify  -dosages_in  cassava.dsgm  -pedigrees_in ptable  -cluster cassava.clustout

Here ptable has the offspring id, followed by the two parents’ ids in the first 3 tab-separated columns. The files with duplicate accessions removed will then be  u\_cassava.dsgm  and  u\_ptable.

Checking pedigrees in a file. 
We can check whether the pedigrees in u\_ptable are correct as follows:

	find_parents  -in u_cassava.dsgm  -ped u_ptable  -out cassava.fpout  

This will just check the pedigrees read from u\_ptable, without searching for alternative pedigrees.

This generates output with one line for each accession. The most useful
The first column contains the accession id.  
This is followed by:

| Column | content |
| --- | --- |
| 1 | id of the progeny accession |
| 2 | the letter 'P' to indicate a pedigree read from a file. |
| 3 | id of the first parent.  |
| 4 | id of the second parent. |
| 7 | hgmr w.r.t. first parent. |
| 9 | hgmr w.r.t. second parent. | 
| 11 | forbidden triple rate (FTR) |
| 16 | apparent crossover max (ACC) [phased data only]|

Columns 5-11 contain quantities calculated using unphased genotype information.   
	
If the genotype data is phased there are an additional 5 columns, columns 12-16,  
containing quantities calculated using phased genotype information. The most interesting of these is usually column 16, the 'apparent crossover count' (ACC)  

These should both be small if the parents are correct. 

![FTR_vs_ACR](./for_readme/FTR\_vs\_ACR\.png "title")

finding likely parents if pedigrees are not available:

	find_parents  -in u_cassava.dsgm  -out cassava_noped.fpout 

Now the output has ‘-’ characters where the fields for the pedigree (cols 3-18) would be.

**Converting from vcf to dosage matrix** (with each line being one accession)  
vcf\_to\_dsgm     
e.g:    vcf\_to\_dsgm  \-in cassava\_maf010.vcf  \-out cassava\_maf010.dsgm   \-prob 0.85 

This produces output in a different format, with each line containing an accession’s id followed by the genotypes for that accessions, coded  as the dosage of the reference allele: 0, 1, 2, or X for missing data. However, in the case of phased data, a heterozygous genotype will be coded as either \-1, or \+1, with the sign indicating the phase. ( \-prob 0.85 means that if there is a GP field, the dosage must have an ‘estimated probability’ of at least 0.85, or it is set to missing data in the output file. ) This will also filter out accessions with greater than the default max proportion of missing data, which is 50%; those accessions are put in a separate file ‘rejected\_accessions.dsgm’ .

**Removing duplicate accessions**:

duplicate\_search  This finds pairs of accessions which have very similar genotypes, specifically, agmr (the proportion of markers at which the two accessions differ) is small. (How small? By default, \< 0.2  )

clusterer   Find clusters of accessions which are very similar and may be regarded as duplicates, taking as input the output from duplicate\_search. It constructs a graph whose vertices are accessions and with an edge joining each sufficiently similar pair of accessions. Clusterer requires the user to specify how similar two accessions must be to be joined by an edge. Specifically the user specifies a maximum distance (agmr). The clusters are defined as the connected components of the resulting graph. This means that two accessions are in the same cluster if it is possible to get from one to the other by traversing the edges of the graph. So if A and B are joined by an edge, and so are B and C, then A and C belong to the same cluster and are considered duplicates, even if (as may occasionally happen) A and C are too dissimilar to be joined by an edge. The recommended

uniquify  Takes as input a dosage matrix file, a cluster file (output of clusterer), and (optionally) a pedigree file. For each cluster of duplicates, one representative is chosen to keep (the one with the least missing data). All other accessions in the cluster are deleted from the dosage matrix output. If a pedigree file is input also, lines with offspring that are not representatives (i.e. the others in a cluster of duplicates which are not the one being kept) are deleted, and each other (parental) ids is replaced with the representative. 

E.g: 

duplicate\_search  \-in cassava\_maf010.vcf.dsgm  \-out cassava\_maf010.vcf.dsout

clusterer  \-in cassava\_maf010.vcf.dsout  \-out cassava\_maf010.clustererout  \-dcluster 0.03

uniquify \-dosages\_in cassava\_maf010.vcf.dsgm \-pedigrees\_in pedtable3col  \-cluster cassava\_maf010.clustererout

Finding parents:  
find\_parents
